[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Welcome to the Better podcast where we have conversations about AI software dev and all kinds of new technology. I\'m one of your host Richard and I\'m joined by I\'m James. I\'m Josh. And I\'m Chris. Hey Chris, so it\'s really good to see you.'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We\'ve been trying to organize this podcast for a while but we\'re glad to finally have you on. Um for those of you who have no idea who Chris is, I\'m going to give him a chance to introduce himself. So who are you Chris? Yeah, my name\'s Chris Penningston. I\'m the DX'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'engineer over at Resend. We\'re an email API for developers. I also have a YouTube channel Coding in Public that I\'ve had for the last several years as well. So that\'s how I think we connected is through both those things and excited to'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'chat about that and and anything else you all want to talk about. I know cool video setup with your mic. &gt;&gt; [laughter] &gt;&gt; That\'s thanks to Resend. Yeah. Yeah, so we can get into that a bit later. But what would you say helped you get into Resend cuz you\'ve done a lot of'

[00:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'things in your past. So how would you explain that journey of getting into Resend? Yeah, I mean it\'s it\'s hard not to just say that I feel super lucky. That\'s a lot of it. I just feel like right time right place with a lot of stuff and connected with the Zenon in'

[01:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'particular. He\'s the CEO of Resend. I started my YouTube channel kind of as a chance for me to kind of talk through what I was learning and one of the things I was learning at the time in 2023 was React email'

[01:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and then Resend when it came along. I think Zenon actually reached out and gave me access to the beta and I posted about both both of those things right around the time that they launched. I didn\'t know it at the time but when the'

[01:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'team saw it then Zenon reached out to me. We just kind of struck up a friendship and then I think we met in San Francisco in 2024 that summer. I was in town and I just messaged him and said hey, do you want to connect?'

[01:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And he\'s a super busy guy and I figured he didn\'t have time but he did and we ended up just mostly chatting about life. Like it wasn\'t me trying to pitch myself to him or I didn\'t you know, they didn\'t have an existing role open, but we kind of struck up a friendship and he'

[01:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reached out that fall and just said, "Hey, we have this DX role open. I\'d love to have you consider it." And I hadn\'t really even thought that direction. Um and uh one thing just led to another and felt like it was a good'

[02:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fit and it\'s the people at Resend are really what make it. Um and uh there\'s a real camaraderie with the team and so all that kind of fell into place, met Zeno, met the team, and uh jumped right on board, and I think it was like 4'

[02:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'weeks from him talking to me to me being in Brazil with the entire team. So it was a pretty quick turnaround uh once everything happened. Uh yeah, and I just feel super lucky to have a chance to be able to like teach people Resend and uh try to push what'

[02:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'re doing to others in a way that\'s hopefully friendly to devs and not super salesy. It\'s not really my nature anyhow, so uh yeah, that\'s that\'s the brief version of the journey. Nice. I think I got some misinformation from Gok cuz apparently'

[02:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you made a massive video on your channel about React Email that got loads of views and they reached out to you from there, but I guess that was incorrect. Uh was it That\'s not totally wrong cuz that\'s how I first met Zeno cuz he he reached out to me having seen that first'

[03:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video and said, "Hey, um yeah, basically like, you know, I\'d love to connect." And so we kind of started chatting over there. Then I did the one on Resend, then we met in person. So it kind of it started there. That\'s the first thing I think that'

[03:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'brought me onto their radar. Nice. Okay, so AI isn\'t completely hallucinating from that side. Not this time. &gt;&gt; [laughter] &gt;&gt; I was saying uh before the podcast started actually, one of my first videos on like developer YouTube is React'

[03:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Email. It was the third video I ever made was on React Email. So sort of I think it was a similar time in like 2023 when I made it um React Email first came out, but yeah. &gt;&gt; [laughter] &gt;&gt; Yeah, I didn\'t even know it had just come out. I think I I did a video within'

[03:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a week or something of it coming out. I just saw it on Twitter and thought, "Oh, this is cool." And I did a video on it. So lucky timing. Did you have a full-time job at the time that you guys connected or was YouTube kind of the main thing at the time? Yeah, YouTube'

[03:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'was the like the side thing that I was doing. So, it wasn\'t my main thing. I I helped at my church. I helped I did I had like a side thing that I was doing myself and then I also worked part-time'

[04:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'at a company doing documentation and I did that for about 8 years. So, that was kind of my main thing that documentation job. So, this you know, life was kind of multiple things all at once and the YouTube thing was honestly just a side thing. Like when I first started'

[04:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'YouTube, I didn\'t tell my wife for 6 months. I just would record and talk and like put it up. I never talked to anyone about it. It wasn\'t supposed to be a thing. I didn\'t mean for anyone to ever see it. Like it was just I\'m very verbal and I need to kind of talk it out to'

[04:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'know if I know something and you know, you all know doing videos like sometimes you can sit down to record and you\'re like, I don\'t really understand how this works and so I need to like I need to start over and so there\'s been lots of times where it was'

[04:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'just like me trying to talk something out. I\'d record it. It didn\'t work cuz I\'m like I clearly don\'t understand this. So, I\'d redo it. So, it was always just the side thing. And then eventually I\'d get a video out talking through it in a way that I felt comfortable that I'

[04:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'understood whatever the topic was. So, yeah, so the the YouTube was always a side thing and kind of the other roles were the things I mostly spent my time on, but no development experience before recent really like as far as like part'

[05:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of a company or anything like that. So, like I said, I just feel super lucky and yeah, super yeah, glad that Zeno\'s taking a chance on me. Yeah, teaching or like yeah, like creating content or even teaching like'

[05:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'just teaching myself helps a lot in just understanding how things work and putting the pieces together. So, super blessed for that. Yeah, it\'s it\'s like you think you know something and then you go to talk through it and you\'re'

[05:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like, I really have no idea what I\'m doing and and then there becomes this artificial thing where you do it enough that you like you prepare these videos and you can it out there, but you it\'s very prepared. And so, one of the things'

[05:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I started doing a couple years ago is I started live streaming just literally sitting down and starting something fresh. And cuz I\'m like, I need to hit the wall a little bit more and really see, do I know something? Because I got to the point where I could carry the'

[06:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video pretty quickly that made sense, but I didn\'t really understand it all or I had to look up so much stuff during it. Um and so, I feel like live streaming is like the ultimate like, do you actually know what you\'re talking about?'

[06:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And a lot of times you don\'t. And you hit your head against the wall ton, and that\'s just part of the process, but I think if you\'re not afraid of failure, um and you\'re not afraid of like hitting those walls, whether it\'s in public or not, you know, isn\'t important, but I'

[06:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'think you can really stretch and grow. Um but you have to kind of be comfortable with that feeling, which is honestly kind of what makes a dev. Like, you have to be willing to hit the wall over and over and over again and say, I\'ll I\'m going to figure this out. I\'m going'

[06:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to research it. Um and now with AI, you know, some of that\'s easier and some of it\'s easier to avoid cuz you can kind of skip past you having to know stuff. I think it\'s really impressive that you kind of came into this with no professional coding'

[06:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'experience. Like, I I wouldn\'t know where to start when it comes to make a video. So, how did you find your topics? Cuz you\'ve got stuff on Astro, you\'ve got stuff on React. Um how did you find out what to make videos on? Yeah, I feel like for me it was very organic, the way'

[07:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it all happened. I was literally just whatever I learned that week, that\'s what I did a video on. And that\'s how I\'ve always been with my channel. Um there\'s no problem if somebody wants to make it a career or a big thing or try to draw attention. Um I think that can'

[07:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'be a really helpful way to um to gain an audience, a community, all that kind of stuff. But for me, it\'s never been that, and I\'ve I\'ve had a lots of chances to make it that, but I\'ve really just tried to keep it to whatever I\'m doing that week, that\'s what I do a video on, which'

[07:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'means I don\'t have like I don\'t have any videos that have blown up uh like traditional, you know, dev blown up. I\'ll have several with 100,000 or something like that over several years, but I I don\'t never had anything, I'

[07:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'don\'t think, approach a million or anything close to that. Um cuz it\'s just whatever I\'m learning. So, it\'s not like hype topics. Um so, literally when I sat down, I was like, "Okay, I\'m going to learn this JavaScript concept, then I\'m going to do a video on it." Uh I\'m learning this'

[07:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'thing, and I happen to do a lot of stuff with Astro when it was first kind of in beta, and it made sense to me, especially like as it added features, I had this progress in my own understanding where it was like, "Oh, I I would be really nice if I could do'

[08:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'some things on the server." And I didn\'t even understand the difference between like server-side rendering and static rendering. Like and then it was like Astro was adding stuff as I was needing to learn it. Um and so, a lot of the Astro stuff is just like'

[08:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that\'s what I did stuff on because I was learning it along the way. Um so, I think for me it was a very organic process where whenever I learn something, I teach it, and that just happened to progress in a way that gave enough attention where yeah, I I feel'

[08:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like uh lucky in that way that I got connected to people. Um but yeah, there was no intentionality in it, which I know is a you know, like a big leg up to have a right where I have. Yeah, I think I saw a very healthy place'

[08:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to be, not wanting to kind of chase hype topics and and talk about what you\'re learning. Um I would say it it was a kind of profitable place to be on YouTube a while back, but now it\'s completely changed. I think a lot of'

[08:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'creators are saying you can\'t make money doing tutorials. You either have to do hype topics or entertaining things. Um how do you feel about that, and is that going to change the direction of your channel? I think for me, there\'s a lot of truth in that if you\'re really trying'

[09:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to make a career out of it. I think I am I feel like I\'m lucky that I I\'ve never tried to make it that thing. So, it\'s always been a fun side thing. It\'s always been a way for me to It\'s kind of been for me, like hopefully not in a selfish way, but just like I need the'

[09:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'chance to talk out what I\'m learning. Um I do think that like views are down like crazy across a lot of more traditional like walk-throughs. I think you all have done really, really well, and so I think you\'ve kind of have this'

[09:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'nice blend of like being educational. It\'s not like a straight walk-through. It\'s more like conceptual stuff a lot of times. Like Richard, I love it when you get out your notepad and start drawing. I\'m like, "Man, I need to do that.'

[09:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That\'s such a good idea." Um so I think there is a way to teach um that captures a lot of that. Um but I think traditional walk-through tutorials you won\'t get the views maybe you used to three or four years ago. For'

[09:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'me, I think because that\'s never really been my target, that\'s not a huge deal for me. I have kind of fallen off YouTube the last several months, but that\'s mostly because I\'m really the only person at Reason doing all all of our marketing, all of our education, and'

[10:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I have been uh we hired somebody and then uh she\'s another DXN gear for us, but has moved to events pretty much entirely. And so um I\'m kind of by myself, so I just don\'t really have capacity right now. Um so it\'s mostly'

[10:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'been by nature of just the way life is right now. We\'re trying to hire, and so once I get somebody else, I think that will free up some more of my time. I don\'t know exactly what that will look like going forward uh for my channel. I think probably I will keep doing the'

[10:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'types of stuff I\'m doing, but I would love to get both more conceptual in some things and then more detailed in others. So my tentative plan is to like do more conceptual topics and my quick deep dives on stuff. Um and then also to do'

[10:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'more slow stuff where I\'m like learning something from scratch, teaching it from scratch for myself. I don\'t think those will do as well, but I\'m okay with that. Like it\'s uh like I said, for me my motivation is kind of been singular'

[11:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'since I started, and that helps me I think kind of pick my true north and just stick with that, and I I feel lucky to be able to do that and not have to worry too much about views, but who knows? We\'ll see how it goes. I think a quite a good example of that'

[11:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is BashBunny. She does quite well on sort of live streaming. I think she\'s going through a Rust journey at the moment. Um and yeah, just sort of teaching herself that, and I think that\'s quite a good example of there is still an audience for people watching people code still'

[11:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'without AI in the way. Yeah, it\'s interesting. Like when I don\'t use AI, I get a lot of comments like um I\'m so glad that I finally hit somebody who\'s not using AI, you know, so I think there is this fatigue as well. Um'

[11:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but I think there needs to be a a way to kind of do both, you know, because it it has changed coding fundamentally and it will continue to do that. And I think there\'s a way in which like you have to figure out what this new world looks'

[11:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like. But I also think that there is something just really tactile about just touching the syntax like and I just like doing that. And so I think I\'ll always have a soft spot in my heart for it and probably will always do some of that'

[12:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'kind of like non-AI coding just for fun. Yeah, I I can\'t imagine how you have the time to do that cuz you\'ve got recent, you\'ve got home life, family life. Um how you finding the time to make your own videos'

[12:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and to learn new skills and to write code by hand all that stuff? I think like a lot of devs like I\'m very curious and always finding ways to like duplicate stuff so uh you know, I\'ll I\'ll I have three'

[12:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'kids. Um so even like little things like we I coach two of my girls soccer football. Um But uh yeah, as we uh as I coach them I\'m like, oh I could spin up a little website for this. And so it\'s like'

[12:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'something I do with them. So I sit down with them, we do that together and I\'m like, oh there\'s this concept I\'d like to figure out how to like stream this thing in from the server. So I\'ve done that before. Uh we had some kittens at one point that we had to uh sell um and so we I sat down with my girls, they helped me code'

[12:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the the page then or like design the page and then we coded it and it looked very much like a six- and eight-year-old at the time I think um you know, designed it. So I try to like blend a lot of life together like that. Um I\'ve got like a 3D printer so I I was'

[13:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'working on some random app with my son the other day and doing the same kind of thing. Uh I\'m really into Liverpool Football Club. Hopefully that doesn\'t uh destroy my reputation with any of you.'

[13:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Um but and so is my son. So we\'ve like spun up a lot of fun things like that. So I think I just try to kind of bring that uh creativity to all the different aspects of life and I love like doing like crafts and arts'

[13:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and like I do a lot of that kind of stuff with my kids. So, I I just I have a lot of energy for that and when I\'m doing it with other people, uh like it doesn\'t feel like it pulls me away from them. It feels like it draws me toward them. Um so, whether it\'s friends, um yeah, or'

[13:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'my kids, uh like I try to spend a lot of time like using that creativity in all these different aspects of life and then I learned stuff that overlays and it makes it easy to use it at work or makes'

[13:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it easy to use uh with my channel. Um usually my channel I\'m recording early in the morning. Um and so, I\'ll usually record like 5:30, 6:00 in the morning. I get up pretty early. Um and so, that\'s kind of my channel'

[14:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'time when I have it and then um yeah, uh work takes the rest of the day and then in the evening sometimes I\'ll do stuff with my kids. Um so, I I don\'t know if that really solves or answers your question, but yeah, just try to bring that creativity'

[14:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to all of life and make it connect me to people instead of hold me away from people. I was just going to say I think that\'s one of the coolest things about sort of AI coding I found is getting a lot more people who like you don\'t have to go'

[14:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'back and teach the syntax of HTML, React, all of that to to people necessarily. You can say like just prompt Claude and then we can sort of talk through an understanding of generally what\'s happening. And it\'s a lot easier obviously to get someone\'s like first app out there is is'

[14:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'so much easier now. Um and I think yeah, AI is great for sort of like micro sites I found. Like any small thing I have now instead of sort of Googling if there\'s a service out there, I\'ll just be like Claude, can you make this because I'

[14:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mean, I\'m its only user, so I don\'t necessarily care that it\'s the best quality it is. So, yeah, it\'s it\'s been nice and yeah, it\'s cool to hear that you\'re sort of using it with your kids in that way. Yeah, yeah, it\'s definitely sped up a lot of that kind of stuff and it helps'

[15:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'them come up with ideas and like one of them they wanted to do a library with their friends, so they built all these custom little books and we built a a website that they could check books in and out of and it was just like the four of these little kids, you know,'

[15:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a couple of my girls and a couple of their friends, but like that\'s a super fun thing to get to do and they felt like super inspired and like, "Oh, can we do it like this?" And you know, normally I could I couldn\'t have time for that. Um, so I think there are ways in which like, um, the my my friend who'

[15:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'works at Recend, uh, her name Christina, she says like apps can be like a little home cooked meal. Like you can just like bake somebody a little meal and it doesn\'t have to be super important and AI makes that easier to do. Um, because'

[15:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you could do that very quickly. You know, I I wish I had that as a kid because I started learning to code because of Minecraft. I wanted to add plugins to it and that meant I had to learn Java, which &gt;&gt; [laughter]'

[16:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; I don\'t know how I did it, but I I got through it. &gt;&gt; Yeah, that\'s impressive. Yeah, I I was going to say, you said you\'ve got two girls and one boy and I\'ve got two girls and I think when I had my first girl, this might be too much information, but when I had my first girl, I could get away with keeping the toilet seat up,'

[16:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but now I I can\'t do that. It\'s uh always has to be down. I don\'t know what it\'s like in your house with the balance, but there\'s there\'s a lot going on. Yeah, you got to change your life as a girl dad. Yeah, exactly. Anyway, let\'s talk about'

[16:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what you do at Recend. So it sounds like you you have a lot going on. You do videos, documentation, you wrote the email skills. Um, what exactly is your canonical job role and title? What are you supposed to be doing? Yeah, I mean'

[16:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it\'s it\'s kind of connects to a lot of things in the company at you know, generally speaking it\'s in the category of like DevRel. Um, we call it DX engineer because we wanted to like appeal to people who are'

[16:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'more development mindset. Um, and so yeah, the it goes from everything from docs to blog posts, change logs, all of our social content, all the videos, education, kind of dev zero on every'

[17:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'part of the product, um, and connecting a lot with people at events, uh, speaking, like that kind of thing. So anything in that general realm. Um, but like I\'ve touched product, I\'ve, you know, shipped features before too. So,'

[17:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like it\'s it ends up being fairly comprehensive. And as the team has grown, like there\'s just more and more stuff we\'re doing. So, it it\'s feels super cool to be able to talk about Resend to people. I kind of view my role as not just about the'

[17:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'product. Like I think obviously I want people to understand what we do at Resend. But I think a lot of it too is like helping push people\'s voice internally in the company outward. I mentioned earlier that'

[17:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Resend really is about the people for me. And we have such amazing developers and designers and success engineers. Like they\'re doing so much. And so a lot of what I\'m trying to do is say like how could I amplify their voices?'

[17:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, a lot of times like I\'m ghostwriting stuff for them. I\'m taking an idea that they had that they mentioned in a meeting and I\'m like, "Hey, could I do a quick like 20-minute interview with you about how this architecture works and why we chose this?" And like could we post this as more of an engineering'

[18:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'post? I\'ll do all the work, but you know, we\'ll I\'ll let you review it and then we\'ll push it out. So, a lot of it for me isn\'t just about the product. It\'s really about the way we think at Resend. It\'s like a very very culture-first company.'

[18:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And I hope it stays that way. It\'s it\'s hard as you as you grow larger to kind of keep that, but that\'s a lot of what I think of is not just pushing the product, but pushing the people out to everyone else as well. So, that\'s kind of the full scope of my'

[18:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'role is anything and all that stuff I mentioned. And a lot of people think that way too at Resend. So, Zeno, the CEO, is very much is very good at social media talking about what we\'re doing. And a lot of our'

[18:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'engineers will like post their own stuff as well. So, it\'s it\'s not like I\'m the only one who cares about getting stuff out to others. But I\'m not like a traditional marketer in any sense of the way of the word. When when Zeno hired me, I asked him'

[18:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like, "All right, from marketer to like educator, where is this role?" Cuz I\'m like past the needle over here. I don\'t care at all about this. And he\'s like, "It\'s fine. We we really just want to talk to people about what we\'re doing and and let it be a more natural organic'

[19:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'thing." And and so that\'s kind of how I view myself as like educating people about the product and about the people at Resend. When you joined, how big was the company and how big are you guys now? I was the 10th hire. Um, I think we are around 45,'

[19:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '46, something like that now and I joined like a year and a half ago. Cool. Um, I was going to say something we spoke about in the email that Resend is very good at getting clothes to'

[19:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'recommend it and I have no idea how you\'ve done that. Um, whenever I build something I need to email, clothes code always say use Resend even though I\'m sure there are many other alternatives out there. It was just get me to use Resend. So, yeah, can you speak to what,'

[19:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
